post_text: The Edna Karr High School family mourns the loss of legendary coach, teacher, and friend, Coach Don Wattigny. Coach Wattigny led the Cougars as our first Varsity Head Coach and led Karr to its first state championship in 1993. We thank Coach Wattigny for his impactful dedication to our school. He was truly Second to None and will be missed.

shared_text:
InspireNOLA Charter Schools
January 17 at 10:34 PM ¬∑

We are looking forward to another year of Edna Karr High School football excellence under the direction of Head Coach Brice Brown.

"We are honored that Coach Brown is going to continue to guide our scholars, on and off the field, and expand the legacy that is our Karr football program. We appreciate all he's done for our scholars, athletes and Edna Karr," said Harold Juluke, InspireNOLA Charter Schools Athletic Director

"As I enter my sixth year as head football coach at Edna Karr, I am grateful for the opportunity to work with such a special group of young men and coaches. Edna Karr is a special place to me and I am excited to see what our team will accomplish in the future. "We have a great group of student-athletes returning for the 2020 season and I am ready to get back to work as we continue to be second to none," said Brice Brown, Edna Karr Head Football Coach

post_text:
Several of our beginner art students will have their art on display as a part of a joint art exhibition at My City and Me, a 5-day high school arts exhibition at Tulane Hillel, in partnership with Newcomb Art Museum, kicking off with an opening night today from 5:30-7:00 p.m.

Opening night will be a festive affair with live music, free food from Rimon Restaurant helmed by renowned Chef Daniel Esses, and most importantly, lots of beautiful, New Orleans-themed art. The exhibit will be open every day from Tuesday April 2nd through Sunday April 7th (except Saturday, April 6th). Come out and support the work of these talented teens and the beauty of New Orleans.
#SecondToNone

The values instilled at Karr extend far beyond the field of play and it's a unique experience for every player who has been a part of the program.

"I don't think I'm going to get this anywhere else," Devin Bush said of the camaraderie the Cougars have. "At any other program I don't feel I would be the person I am today. I learned football lessons, and it also related to life lessons. We're big on learning about life lessons. Playing for Karr you're going to be a better man, a better football player and you're going to be everything that you want to be."

Today's speaker was none other than Class of 1997 graduate and WDSU News Anchor, Gina Swanson Gray. Congratulations to each of them as they continue to live up to our motto, "Second to None".

post_text:
The Orleans Parish School Board in conjunction with InspireNOLA Charter Schools broke ground at the site of the new Edna Karr High School Campus. Located at 4400 General Meyer Avenue, the building will be 153,332 square feet and will accommodate Grades 9 through 12. The building will include fifty-two classrooms consisting of thirty-one Core Academic Classrooms, four Special Education Classrooms, two Visual Arts Classrooms, four Music/Performing Arts Classrooms, four CTE classrooms, three ROTC classrooms and other learning spaces. The 1,200 Student capacity building will also include two gymnasiums: one competition gym and one practice gym.

The $48.8 Million School will be ADA and Energy Efficient LEED Silver compliant. Construction completion is projected for Summer 2020.

The Orleans Parish School Board in conjunction with InspireNOLA Charter Schools broke ground at the site of the new Edna Karr High School Campus. Located at 4400 General Meyer Avenue, the building will be 153,332 square feet and will accommodate Grades 9 through 12. The building will include fifty-two classrooms consisting of thirty-one Core Academic Classrooms, four Special Education Classrooms, two Visual Arts Classrooms, four Music/Performing Arts Classrooms, four CTE classrooms, three ROTC classrooms and other learning spaces. The 1,200 Student capacity building will also include two gymnasiums: one competition gym and one practice gym.

The $48.8 Million School will be ADA and Energy Efficient LEED Silver compliant. Construction completion is projected for Summer 2020.
